Looking at the mutation, the change is in the inner loop condition: `i < length` becomes `i <= length`. This means the loop will try to access `arguments[length]` which is `undefined`, potentially causing an error or unexpected behavior.

Let me analyze the code:
- The outer loop runs `for (var i = 1; i < length; i++)`
- Inside it, there's `var s = arguments[i]` (the placeholder)
- The mutation changes the inner loop to `i <= length`, so it will access `arguments[length]` which is `undefined`

When `s` is `undefined`, neither `typeof s === 'function'` nor `s && typeof s === 'object'` will be true, so it just skips. But wait - the mutation is in the inner `for` loop declaration itself, which would cause an infinite loop or off-by-one error.

Actually, looking more carefully: the `<PLACEHOLDER>` replaces the inner `for` loop declaration. The outer loop already has `for (var i = 1; i < length; i++)`. The placeholder IS the inner loop's `for` statement. So the mutated code has `for (var i = 1; i <= length; i++)` as the inner loop, which would cause `i` to go one past the end, accessing `undefined`.

When `s` is `undefined`, the code does nothing extra. But the issue is that the inner loop resets `i` to 1, so the outer loop's `i` gets overridden. This creates an infinite loop!

